UFO Sightings Through the Data Science Pipeline¶

By Melissa(Shiqi) Chen , Andrea Soto and Liu Guanhua

Introduction¶

Most of us do not realize that data science plays a role in various aspects of our daily lives. For example, data sience can have applications in the areas of marketing and advertising, healthcare, government, image recognition, cybersecuirty and many more. Data science is a rapidly rising, interdisciplinary field that involves an understanding of various scientific, mathematical, computational and design techniques in order to extract insight from large amounts of data to solve real world problems. More and more industries are noticing the importance of this field for making smart, informed, and even profitable everyday decisions. Since there is an increasing need for knowledgeable and able data scientists, it is important for more people to acquire the necessary skills so that they can confidently enter this exciting and growing field.

In this introductory tutorial we will choose a dataset and walk through the steps of the data science pipeline in manner that is easy to understand and follow. The pipeline consists of the following steps:

  1. Data Collection
  2. Data Processing
  3. Exploratory Analysis and Visualization
  4. Map Anaylisis (Machine learning)
  5. Hypothesis Testing and Machine Learning
  6. Conclusion

This tutorial can help those with an understanding of scripting languages but who are new to the data science methodology as a whole. It can also help more experieced data scientists who are perhaps unfamiliar with Python and the various libraries availble that simplify the data analysis process.

By the end of the tutorial, you will have learned how to search for and derive meaningful information from a large dataset and convey your findings in a visually, insightful way.

Motivation for Analyzing UFO Sightings Data¶

Many of us think about the possibility of life existing elsewhere in the universe and though we often hear about people seeing UFOs, we don't usually think of this as a problem we can analyze computationally. With this dataset, we have access to thousands of UFO sighting reports with attributes such as data and time of sighting, state, country, latitude and longitude, and duration of sighting. With these kind of data, we could start asking some interesting questions. For example:

  • In what areas of the country or at what times of day are we most likely to witness UFOs?
  • Is there a relationship between shape of the UFO and state, or country, or some other attribute?
  • How has the number of UFO sightings changed overtime?

If we can find certain areas that are more particularly prone to UFO sightings or other hidden trends, it could help us predict when the next UFO sightings will happen. This could help us be more prepared to gather better evidence when these events occur and ultimately get closer to discovering other life forms.

Data Collection¶

Before we collect data, we need to think about what topics are of interest and what types of problems we want to solve. There are five ways to collect data:

  • Directly downloading a dataset and loading it from local storage
  • Generate data locally through downloaded code
  • Query data from a database
  • Query an online API(application programming interface)
  • Scrape data from a website

Datasets are commonly formatted as comma-separated value (CSV) files, Javascript Object Notation (JSON) files, HTML, XHTML, or XML files. Python can easily work with any of these file types to easily transform the data into a workable format.

As a new data scientist, you will need to practice the techniques showed in this tutorial. Thankfully, there are many sources online from which we can download datasets for free in order to practice. You also want to make sure that the data you choose is from reliable source so that you can make accurate predictions about the data. Check out the following reputable sources:

  • Kaggle
  • UCI Maching Learning Repository
  • Socrata
  • Amazon Web Services Public Data Sets
  • Google Public Datasets
  • Wikipedia Databases
  • Data World

In this tutorial we are using the UFO Sightings dataset from Kaggle in CSV format. The following code shows how we load the data into the jupyter notebook.

Data Processing¶

To make the data easier to work with, we are using DataFrame from the Pandas library. A DataFrame is a "two-dimensional size-mutable, potentially heterogeneous tabular data structure." You can conceptually think about it as a spreadsheet or a SQL table. This structure allows us to access data by column and row and even makes it possible to iteratively manipulate data.

Now that we have loaded the data, we need to tidy it up. At larger scales, the majority of our time could be spent in the data processing phase because raw datasets are often times messy and incomplete. Therefore we want to clean and organize the data before we start any analysis to minimize errors or inaccuracies and simplify the next steps of the pipeline.

We want to check the data for missing values and either drop the corresponding rows or columns, or put in some value. Then we want to refine the data further by dropping the rows or cols of data we don't need. For example, maybe we're only interested in data from certain years, or data from certain states. We can filter our data to be more concise and dense.

In [4]:
# Clean up the unknown entries by replacing them with Numpy NaN
df = df.replace('unknown', np.NaN)

# Drop unnecessary columns
df.dropna(how="all", inplace=True)
df = df.drop('duration (hours/min)',axis= 1)
df = df.drop('date posted',axis=1)
df = df.drop('comments',axis=1)

# Rename: make the name shorter and easier to call later
df = df.rename(columns = {'duration (seconds)':'duration'})
df = df.rename(columns = {'latitude':'lat'})

# Get ride of the space in our header
df = df.rename(columns = {'longitude ':'long'})

# Convert to numerical number, fix mix type issue
#df['lat']=pd.to_numeric(df['lat'])
df['duration'] = df.duration.str.extract('(\d+)', expand=True).astype(int)
df['lat'] = df.lat.str.extract('(\d+\.\d+)', expand=True).astype(float)

# Get rid of space in column 
df['state'] = df.state.str.extract('(\w+)', expand=True).astype(str)
df['shape'] = df['shape'].str.extract('(\w+)', expand=True).astype(str)
df['state'] = df['state'].str.replace(" ","")
df['shape']=df['shape'].str.replace(" ","")

# Deal with the time 
df['datetime'] = df['datetime'].replace('24:00','00:00',regex=True)

# Convert the date time value
df['datetime']= pd.to_datetime(df['datetime'],format='%m/%d/%Y %H:%M')

# Extract hour from datetime value
hours=df['datetime'].dt.hour
df['datetime_hour'] = hours
df['datetime_year'] = df['datetime'].dt.year
df['datetime_month'] = df['datetime'].dt.month
df['datetime_day'] = df['datetime'].dt.day
df.head()

Exploratory Data Analysis and Visualization¶

Exploratory data analysis is used to obtain a deeper understanding of the dataset we are using. It involves delving into the data in search of interesting relationships between variables, skew, trends, or any issues with the data. We can start this exploration by performing some simple summary statistics such as mean, median, and standard deviation. We can also use EDA to prepare the data for modeling and visualizations so that we can easily view distributions and any patterns. For more information on exploratory data analysis check out this tutorial on Data Camp.

Mean, Median, and SD for UFO Sighting Duration¶

In [4]:

In [5]:
print("median duration in seconds:",df["duration"].median())

median duration in seconds: 180.0
In [6]:
print("standard deviation in seconds:",df["duration"].std())

standard deviation in seconds: 620216.790311

The mean and median are surprisingly and drastically different. The average amount of time a sighting lasts is about 2.5 hours while the median is about 3 minutes long. This information suggests that there is a wide spread of duration values. It's also possible that there are outlier values.

Correlation¶

Next we want to get an idea for potential relationships that may exist in the data. A correlation matrix is a table that shows the correlation coefficients between sets of variables. It allows you to see which pairs of variables have the highest correlation. The closer the coefficient is to +1 or -1, the stronger the relationship is between those 2 variables. The diagonal in the matrix always corresponds to a set of correlation coefficients with a value of 1. This is because the correlation between a variable and itself is always 1.

Word Clouds¶

The clouds give greater prominence to words that appear more frequently in the source text. We can cusromize the relative_scaling and the background color of the wordcloud. In the first anaylsis, we set the background color to black and the second one we set the background color to white.

Notice: We must set the collocations to False when we make the wordcloud, so it will not mistake two consecutive instances of the same word as one word. For example in our case we have a lot of consecutive instances like "ca ca fl", we want to avoid counting "ca ca" as a single word even tho it is sperated by space.

For more information: https://github.com/amueller/word_cloud

def drawCloud(text,color):
    text = text+" "+"STOP"
    #create wordcloud instance
    wordcloud = WordCloud(
                      background_color=color,
                      relative_scaling = 1.0,
                    stopwords="STOP",
                    collocations = False,
                      ).generate(text)
    #show the wordcloud instance
    plt.imshow(wordcloud)
    plt.axis("off")
    plt.show()

DBscan (Machine Learning)¶

DB scan is a density based clustering algorithsm that groups nearby data toegther to form centroids. We can form more than one centroid based on the radius that we set for the clustering algorithsm. In this case, we set the radius to be: epsilon = 0.5 / 6371.0088 km. (6371.0088 is the diameter of the earth in km)

In addition to customizing the radius, we can also customize the minimun number of data points per cluster. In this case, we are going to set the min = 100.

Since we have over 80000 data, and the visual machine is not capable to analyze that many data points, we are going to seprate the data points into different seasons and find out the most popular spots(centroids) for UFO sightings in terms of seasons.

In [22]:

Below is DB scan algorithm for analyzing the data.

Check out the DBscan idea from:http://scikit-learn.org/stable/auto_examples/cluster/plot_dbscan.html#sphx-glr-auto-examples-cluster-plot-dbscan-py

In [23]:
# This method is going to return a panda dataFrame called centroids. 
def DBscan(dataset):
    # Define the needed pram for DBscan. 
    kms_per_radian = 6371.0088       
    epsilon = 0.5 / kms_per_radian
    minSamples = 100     
    coordinates=dataset[['lat','long']].values
    
    # DBscan 
    db = DBSCAN(eps=epsilon, min_samples=minSamples, algorithm='ball_tree', metric='haversine').fit(np.radians(coordinates))
    y = db.labels_
    #centroid are represnt by latitude and longitude 
    centroids = pd.DataFrame(columns=['lat','lon'])
    X = pd.DataFrame(coordinates, columns=['lat','lon'])
    Y = pd.DataFrame(y, columns=['label'])
    res = pd.concat([X,Y], axis=1, join='inner')
    n_clusters = len(set(res['label'])) - (1 if -1 in set(res['label']) else 0)

    for i in range(n_clusters):
        el = res[res['label'] == i].mean(axis=0).drop('label')
        centroids = centroids.append(el, ignore_index=True)

    return centroids

We are going to drop the unknow data using 'dropna' from panda before we do the DB scan algorithsm

In [24]:
spring = spring.dropna(how='any')

Hypothesis Testing and Machine Learning¶

Machine learning is a method of data analysis that automates analytical model building. We'll use supervised machine learning, and we'll train some predictor using a training dataset. We'll see how well this predictor predicts another dataset, called the test data set.

Hypothesis¶

Base on the graph in Section 4: Line 12, We can see a U shaped relationship between the sightings per hour and the time of a day. So we decide to choose the sightings per hours within a day to predict. The goal of our machine learning predictor will then be to take a time of day, and correctly output the count of sighting per hours.

Polyfit¶

The algorithm we will use is numpy's polyfit. Polyfit will practice on a set of x and y points and a degree n, and return a set of n+1 coefficients specifying a degree n polynomial to best fitting those points. The coefficients can then be used to predict y given any value of x. The outcome is the count of sighting per hours, so we choose it to be y. Then the time of day we choose it to be x. Here is a little example on a small subset of our data to see how this works. We use the Polyfit of Numpy based on this resouce: https://docs.scipy.org/doc/numpy/reference/generated/numpy.polyfit.html.

In [123]:
#select 500 random points from dataset
sampled_dataframe = df.copy().sample(500)
sampled_test = sampled_dataframe.groupby(['datetime_hour']).size().reset_index(name='counts')
#do a polynomial fit with degree 5
sampled_fit = np.polyfit(sampled_test['datetime_hour'], sampled_test['counts'], 5)
sampled_poly = np.poly1d(sampled_fit)
#Generate linearly spaced vector with from 0-23 hours with 100 data points
sampled_x = np.linspace(0,23, 100)
sampled_y = sampled_poly(sampled_x)
#plot the graph
plt.plot(sampled_x, sampled_y)
plt.plot(sampled_test['datetime_hour'], sampled_test['counts'], '-')
plt.title('Example using random sample of 500 points')
plt.ylabel('Sighting Per Hour')
plt.xlabel('Hour of a day')
plt.show()

Splitting our Data¶

Now we're ready to split our data into test and training. We'll shuffle our data randomly before splitting into test and train samples so that make sure there exists difference between test and train data. Generally we put more data into training than testing, so we'll choose to have 2/5th of our data as test data.

In [124]:
#randomly shuffle the data and set the cutoff point to be 3/5
shuffled_df = df.copy().sample(frac=1)
cutoff = int(len(shuffled_df)*(3/5))

#split the data
train_df = shuffled_df[0:cutoff]
test_df = shuffled_df[cutoff::]
Cross-Validation¶

In order to test the accuracy of our sample, we are going to partition our sample into training set to train our model. And in this case, we are going to use 20 folds corss validation. The original sample is randomly partitioned into 20 equal size subsamples. And the final validation is based on the rest of the data. Lear more about cross validation: http://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/cross_validation.html

In [125]:
from sklearn import cross_validation
import sklearn.metrics
import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings('ignore')
#20-fold cross-validation
train_data= train_df.groupby(['datetime_hour']).size().reset_index(name='counts')
x_train = train_data['datetime_hour']
y_train = train_data['counts']
cv = cross_validation.KFold(len(x_train), n_folds=20)

validation_errors = []
train_errors = []
for degree in range(1,20):
    avg_train_error = 0
    avg_validation_error = 0
    for testcv, traincv in cv:
        #train our data with training subset
        cv_fit = np.polyfit(x_train[traincv], y_train[traincv], degree)
        cv_poly = np.poly1d(cv_fit)

        #test accuracy of data using squared error
        #training error
        predicted_train = cv_poly(x_train[traincv])
        train_error = (predicted_train - y_train[traincv])**2
        avg_train_error += np.mean(train_error)/20

        #validation error
        predicted_validation = cv_poly(x_train[testcv])
        validation_error = (predicted_validation - y_train[testcv])**2
        avg_validation_error += np.mean(validation_error)/20
        
    train_errors.append(avg_train_error)
    validation_errors.append(avg_validation_error)
In [126]:
#plot the graph
plt.plot(train_errors, label='Training Error')
plt.plot(validation_errors, label='Validation Error')
plt.legend()
plt.title('Training and Validation Error')
plt.ylabel('Error')
plt.xlabel('Degree')
plt.show()

We can see that from 0 to 16.5 the error is 0 which means we have a pretty good fit. However, it after degree 16.75, it has the sign of a serious over fitting, since the training error is 0 while the validation error is increasing dramatically.

Hypothesis Analysis¶

The fundamental question we want to ask is whether there is a relationship between time and rate of sightings. Otherwise, we would accept the null hypothesis, that there is no relation. There are many ways to test a hypothesis, but we will use the R2R2 score. The R2R2 test compares the variation for all y values sharing a common x value with the variation from the prediction. If these variations are similar, it implies that most of the error is just due to random deviation from the model. The best possible R2R2 score is 1, and the worst is 0. For more information about the R2R2 score, see http://blog.minitab.com/blog/adventures-in-statistics-2/regression-analysis-how-do-i-interpret-r-squared-and-assess-the-goodness-of-fit.

In [129]:
#calculate r^2 from sklearn 
r2_score = sklearn.metrics.r2_score(y_test, final_poly(x_test))
print(r2_score)

0.490636855776

We usually consider any score above 0.5 as related and close to 0 as unrelated. Our result is 0.491, which appears to be very close to 0.5. It is not a very strong relationship between the hour in a day and the number of sightings, but it does appear to be somewhat related since it is close to 0.5 and not close to 0. Overfitting might occur in the training phase and there are outliers in our dataset.

Conclusion:¶

If you are interested in spotting UFOs, it will be very useful to know where and when most sightings occur. From our anaylysis we can see that Californaia, Florida, Washington and Texas have the most sightings and that most sightings occur between 3 pm and midtnight during the summer month. Some shapes of the UFO are more common than the others. In addition, from our map analysis, we can see that the coastal areas have more sightings than the heartland.

The dataset is rich, there is more information that we can look at, for example we could explore the relationship between the time of the day and the shape of the UFO. Or we can even go deeper to use some text machine learning algorithsm to analyze the people's comments about the sightings in the dataset.

Data science is a fasinating and useful tool for exploring all kinds of readily available datasets that you can find on the internet. The dataset that we are using for our tutorial is from https://www.kaggle.com. It has a lot of other interesting datasets that you can explore. I am sure there are many other sites that would have datasets on just about any topics that you might be interested in.
